                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Ecological Resources:</strong> Shelter/Nesting Material</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scientific-name">Thuja occidentalis 'Smaragd'</div>
        <div class="priority-rank">Low</div>
        <div class="description">Cultivar of native North American conifer. This narrow, pyramid-shaped evergreen grows 12-14 feet tall with dense, bright green scale-like foliage that retains color year-round. Produces small cones. Deer resistant. Provides year-round shelter for birds. Note: Species native to northern regions, not specifically Virginia's Piedmont, but widely adapted.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="species-grid">
        <div class="common-name-section">
            <div class="common-name">Fox Sedge</div>
            <div class="plant-details">
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Type:</strong> Graminoid</div>
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Life Cycle:</strong> Perennial</div>
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Bloom Time:</strong> Late Spring to Early Summer</div>
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Sun:</strong> Full Sun</div>
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Moisture:</strong> Wet</div>
                <div class="detail-line"><strong>Ecological Resources:</strong> Fruit/Nut/Seed, Shelter/Nesting Material</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scientific-name">Carex vulpinoidea</div>
        <div class="priority-rank">Low</div>
        <div class="description">Native sedge to eastern North America including Virginia. This clumping grass-like plant grows 2-3 feet tall with narrow leaves and distinctive spiky brown flower clusters at stem tips. Triangular stems distinguish sedges from true grasses. Thrives in wet to moist soils. Seeds provide food for waterfowl and songbirds. Important component of wetland ecosystems.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="species-grid">
        <div class="common-name-section">
